Apparel Pricing Intelligence¶

1. How does brand reputation statistically correlate with clothing price variations?¶

In [59]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv("clothes_price_prediction_data.csv")

# Group by Brand and calculate mean price
brand_avg_price = df.groupby('Brand')['Price'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False)

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
brand_avg_price.plot(kind='bar', color='skyblue')
plt.title('Average Price by Brand')
plt.xlabel('Brand')
plt.ylabel('Average Price ($)')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')
plt.savefig("average price by brand.png")
plt.show()

3. Are there significant price differences between sizes within the same category?¶

In [61]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv("clothes_price_prediction_data.csv")

# Check if 'Dress' exists
if 'Dress' in df['Category'].unique():
    # Filter and clean data
    dress_df = df[df['Category'] == 'Dress'].dropna(subset=['Size', 'Price'])
    
    # Check validity
    if not dress_df.empty:
        unique_sizes = dress_df['Size'].nunique()
        if unique_sizes > 1:
            plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
            sns.boxplot(x='Size', y='Price', data=dress_df)
            plt.title('Price Distribution by Size (Dress)')
            plt.xlabel('Size')
            plt.ylabel('Price ($)')
            plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')
            plt.show()
        else:
            print(f"Only {unique_sizes} size(s) found. Need at least 2.")
    else:
        print("No data for 'Dress' after cleaning.")
else:
    print("Category 'Dress' not found.")# Filter data for a category
dress_df = df[df['Category'] == 'Dress']

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
dress_df.boxplot(column='Price', by='Size', grid=False)
plt.title('Price Distribution by Size (Dress)')
plt.xlabel('Size')
plt.ylabel('Price ($)')
plt.suptitle('')  # Remove default title
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')
plt.savefig("price distribution by size.png")
plt.show()

<Figure size 1000x600 with 0 Axes>

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))

plt.colorbar(label='Average Price ($)')
plt.title('Price Tiers: Brand vs. Category')
plt.xticks(range(len(pivot_table.columns)), pivot_table.columns)
plt.yticks(range(len(pivot_table.index)), pivot_table.index)

6. What is the distribution of prices for sustainable vs. synthetic materials?¶

In [64]:
# Classify materials as sustainable/synthetic
df['Material_Type'] = df['Material'].apply(lambda x: 'Sustainable' if x in ['Organic Cotton', 'Hemp'] else 'Synthetic')

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.violinplot(
    x='Material_Type', 
    y='Price', 
    data=df, 
    hue='Material_Type',  # Add this line
    palette='pastel', 
    legend=False  # Suppress legend
)
plt.title('Price Distribution: Sustainable vs. Synthetic Materials')
plt.xlabel('Material Type')
plt.ylabel('Price ($)')
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')
plt.savefig("price distribution.png")
plt.show()

8. Can we identify outliers in price vs. attribute combinations?¶

In [66]:
from scipy import stats

# Calculate z-scores for Price
df['Price_Z'] = stats.zscore(df['Price'])
outliers = df[(df['Price_Z'] > 3) | (df['Price_Z'] < -3)]

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.scatter(df['Brand'], df['Price'], alpha=0.6, label='Normal')
plt.scatter(outliers['Brand'], outliers['Price'], color='red', label='Outliers')
plt.title('Price Outliers by Brand')
plt.xlabel('Brand')
plt.ylabel('Price ($)')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(linestyle='--')
plt.savefig("price outliers by brand.png")
plt.show()

11. Which brands demonstrate consistent pricing strategies?¶

In [70]:
brand_cv = df.groupby('Brand')['Price'].agg(['mean', 'std'])
brand_cv['CV'] = (brand_cv['std'] / brand_cv['mean']) * 100

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
brand_cv['CV'].sort_values().plot(kind='bar', color='purple')
plt.title('Price Consistency by Brand (Coefficient of Variation)')
plt.xlabel('Brand')
plt.ylabel('CV (%)')
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')
plt.savefig("price consistency.png")
plt.show()
